<td id="title_text"><h1><a title="Stiffness" class="currentChild" href="Stiffness">Stiffness</a></h1></td>



</tr></table>
</td>
</tr></table></div>



<div id="content" class="content wikipage" lang="en" dir="ltr">
<p id="l1">
A paper property that measures its ability to withstand a bending force. Paper has two basic varieties of stiffness: <a title="Flexural Stiffness" href="Flexural_Stiffness">flexural stiffness</a>, which is a paper's resistance to an externally-applied bending force, and <a title="Handling Stiffness" href="Handling_Stiffness">handling stiffness</a>, which is a paper's ability to support its own weight. Thickness (or <a title="Caliper" href="Caliper">caliper</a>) and <a title="Basis Weight" href="Basis_Weight">basis weight</a> are the chief determinants of a paper's stiffness; generally, a paper's stiffness varies as the cube of thickness (a doubling of caliper produces an eight-fold increase in stiffness). A paper's stiffness is also greater when the bending force is in the <a title="Cross-Grain Direction" href="Cross-Grain_Direction">cross-grain direction</a>, often by a ratio of two-to-one. The degree of stiffness required varies according to end use requirements. 
</p>
